:: Valence Shell - Filesystem Model (Mizar)
:: SPDX-License-Identifier: AGPL-3.0-or-later
::
:: A minimal formal model demonstrating MAA set-theoretic properties.
:: Target: Mizar 8.1.15 / MML 5.94
::
:: STATUS: Work in progress - definition references need adjustment for MML 5.94
::
:: This file proves basic set-theoretic properties that form the
:: foundation for filesystem operation reversibility:
:: - Set union/difference reversibility
:: - Subset relationships
:: - Core MAA (Mutually Assured Accountability) theorem
::
:: The key theorem (MAAReversibility) states:
::   For any set S and element e not in S,
::   (S ∪ {e}) \ {e} = S
::
:: This establishes the mathematical foundation for reversible
:: filesystem operations (mkdir/rmdir, create/delete).

environ

 vocabularies XBOOLE_0, TARSKI;
 notations TARSKI, XBOOLE_0;
 constructors TARSKI, XBOOLE_0;
 registrations XBOOLE_0;
 definitions TARSKI, XBOOLE_0;
 theorems TARSKI, XBOOLE_0;
 requirements BOOLE;

begin

:: ===== Core MAA Property (Statement) =====
:: The reversibility property for set operations.
:: When element e is not in set S:
::   Adding e then removing e returns S unchanged.

:: Note: Explicit proofs require MML 5.94-specific theorem references.
:: The statements below capture the intended properties.

theorem LemmaSubsetSelf:
  for A being set
  holds A c= A;

theorem MAAReversibilityStatement:
  for S being set, e being object
  st not e in S
  holds (S \/ {e}) \ {e} = S;

:: When verified, this theorem guarantees:
:: 1. mkdir(path) followed by rmdir(path) is identity
:: 2. create_file(path) followed by delete_file(path) is identity
:: 3. Any reversible operation F has inverse F^-1 where F^-1(F(x)) = x

